#### Non-parametric tests for numerical data
- parametric tests use means, non-parametrics use ranking of observations of data
##### Sign test (two sample test on paired differences, a non-parametric test)
- ordinal data 
	not relative magnitude but up/down/same (9.2)
##### Wilcoxon Signed(-Rank) Test
- ordinal data
	knowing the magnitude of change (9.3: paired ordinal data
- Instead of means/props, the measure is ranks and signs
- Analog to **paired (dependent) t-test**
- Assumptions
	- sample size is continuous and **loosely symmetric** (but not *necessarily* normal) distribution
	- ***In the homework, justify why you used this test!!!***
- Summary (pg. 343, n= total number...)


Example 9.8 (sign test) : prop.test(18, 40, p=0.5, alternative ="two.sided", correct = TRUE)
- two sample dependent rank test 

##### Wilcoxon Rank-Sum Test
- 2-sample independent test (non-parametric; **t-test** analog)

##### Permutation Test
- *Sum of **ranks*** test  
	- If the rank sum (relative to other ranks) lies in middle = big value
	- If rank sum was at the end = small p-value, not likely due to chance
- If the groups are the same, then the observations will be the same between the two groups
- Where does this one rank in the terms of sameness?
- (pg 362)
- used for EVEN smaller sample sizes
---
#### Non-parametric tests for categorical data
##### Fischer Exact test
- small sample independent proportions
	approximation for Chi Squared Test
	E0 for any 2x2 box is <5

##### McNemar's Test (p402, how-to)
-  dependent ver. of chi-squared test
	E0 for any 2x2 box is <5
- the null is that they're equal

Only discordant pairs (different treatments, different outcomes) matter! With outcomes/same with diftreatments, then it doesn't 

##### RxC contingency tables
Assumptions
-  4/5 of the cells have E0 <5
- No cell has E0 < 1
